NT||at|^B@2^Y@3T|FP||AT|wo more interesting points characterize the deal just analyzed. |
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


AT| The first is the question of your proper play on the third round of hearts. You still have remaining the eight- and five-spot, and you know that Partner originally held at least four hearts. His four must have included the seven-spot, or he would not have played the King immediately.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT|^B@2
If he held four, which card you play can make no difference; but if he held five, your play is very important. If you play the five spot on the third round, your eight will be the highest outstanding heart and will win the fourth round. This will completely shut out Partner's fifth heart, which is good, and he will never be able to cash it in. |
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


NT|^B@2
To provide for the contingency that Partner may have held five hearts originally, you must play your eight on the third round. Then you can play the five on Partner's seven, and his deuce will be good for a trick.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Thus, every heart you played was important - first the Queen,|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


AT| to make sure of driving out Declarer's stopper;|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


AT| second the trey, to tell Partner that you held originally four cards in the suit;|
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


AT| and third the eight on the King, to unblock the suit.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT|^B@2
This is excellent defense - cooperating with Partner to give him the correct count on the hand, and getting out of his way. |
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


NT|^B@2
The second interesting point is how West knew that the trey showed an original holding of four rather than only two hearts. After all, the trey might have been your only card. The answer is simple.|
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT|^B@2
If you had held only two hearts, the Declarer must have held five. Certainly if the Declarer had held five headed by Ace-Jack, he would have bid the suit some time during the auction. Since he did not ever call hearts, let us say, he must have held only three, and you had four.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Almost invariably a clue like this will enable Partner to read your return lead correctly - if you follow established conventions, as recommended here. If no clue is available, you must merely hope that your Partner guesses aright!|
